  "prompt": "Is O-ve universal donor?",
  "response": "No, O-negative (O-) blood is not a universal donor for all blood types, but it is often called the \"universal donor\" for red blood cells. This is because O-negative blood can generally be transfused to any patient in need of red blood cells, regardless of the recipient's blood type, due to the lack of A, B, and Rh antigens on its surface. However, when it comes to plasma transfusions, AB-positive is considered the universal donor because AB plasma contains no antibodies that would attack the recipient\u2019s red blood cells. It is important to match blood types accurately in medical settings to prevent adverse reactions.",
